 \noindent \textbf{\huge {Preface}}
 
 \noindent \indent \textit{A Quick Guide to Special Relativity: An Inquiry into Space and Time} is, as its title hints, not a textbook, but rather a quick theoretical guide to Eintein's theory of special relativity. This book may suit best for miserable undergraduates whose first Modern Physics examination is quickly approaching (unideally the next day). However, readers who have established some intuition or mathematical background on special relativity may also find this text helpful for brushing up their technical understanding of this theory or for first diving into the more ``mathy'' and meaty bits of relativity. This book consists mostly of mathematical descriptions, derivations, and consequences of important concepts in special relativity, and it puts less emphasis on the historical background or intuitive explanations to these ideas. Hence, for readers who are eager to enhance their mathematical mastery of special relativity or looking for an ``equation handbook'', this book should be the way to go. Again, keep in mind that this text is not a textbook. There will be a few sample problems (with solution following immediately). However, readers should not expect to find exercises from this book. Therefore, to truly master special relativity (or anything else really), readers are encouraged to seek out challenging problem sets and more advanced-level theoretical readings on this subject. David J. Morin's \textit{Special Relativity: For the Enthusiastic Beginner} offers a great start.\\
 
